11
00:00:51,420 --> 00:00:55,900
What Not To Do When Making Your Appeal
1. Don’t bring up the past

12
00:00:55,899 --> 00:01:00,489
Bringing up the past, rather good or bad,
will not help you in your cause. The justice

13
00:01:00,490 --> 00:01:05,530
and nobility of your cause will not prevail.
Not only is a man not obliged to be grateful,

14
00:01:05,530 --> 00:01:11,140
gratitude is often a terrible burden that
he gladly discards. It is best to speak pragmatically

15
00:01:11,140 --> 00:01:15,420
to pragmatic people. People rarely act against
their own interests.

16
00:01:15,420 --> 00:01:19,810
Like in the case of the Corcyrans and the
Corinthians who were at the brink of war with

17
00:01:19,810 --> 00:01:24,379
one another. They both wanted to win over
the Athenians as an ally because to do so,

18
00:01:24,379 --> 00:01:28,959
would surely win the war. Both sides were
to send representatives to plead their case

19
00:01:28,959 --> 00:01:33,679
to the Athenians. The Corcyra representative
could only offer one thing and that was an

20
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:38,250
alliance of mutual interests to create a formidable
force that could intimidate the rival state

21
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:42,739
of Sparta. The representative from Corinth
only talked about their past relationship

22
00:01:42,739 --> 00:01:47,560
with Athens and went on to list the many services
Corinth had performed for Athens, and the

23
00:01:47,560 --> 00:01:51,960
importance of showing gratitude to one's friends.
Needless to say, The Athenians were offended

24
00:01:51,959 --> 00:01:56,658
by the Corinthian ambassador by his subtle
way of asking them to feel guilty about past

25
00:01:56,659 --> 00:02:01,740
generosities. The Athenians could have cared
less and allied with the Corcyrans.

26
00:02:01,739 --> 00:02:05,239
2. Don’t Be Trapped In Your Own Wants and
Desires

27
00:02:05,239 --> 00:02:09,228
Do not start from the assumption that the
people you are appealing to have a selfless

28
00:02:09,229 --> 00:02:13,780
interest in helping you. Don’t talk as if
your needs matter to people—they probably

29
00:02:13,780 --> 00:02:18,810
could care less, especially referring to larger
issues: a great cause, or grand emotions such

30
00:02:18,810 --> 00:02:23,640
as love and gratitude when simple, everyday
realities would have much more appeal.

31
00:02:23,639 --> 00:02:28,279
When the Dutch began to arrive in Japan in
great numbers, Ieyasu, the Japanese emperor,

32
00:02:28,280 --> 00:02:32,699
was much relieved. He needed Europeans for
their know-how in guns and navigation, and

33
00:02:32,699 --> 00:02:36,810
here at last were Europeans who cared nothing
for spreading religion—the Dutch wanted

34
00:02:36,810 --> 00:02:41,659
only to trade. Ieyasu swiftly moved to evict
the Portuguese who were desperately trying

35
00:02:41,659 --> 00:02:46,030
to convert the Japanese people to Catholicism.
